## Project Overview

#### There are three projects in the Programming with Music Lab curriculum, one for each coding concept: sequencing, loops, and functions. Below is the rubric and a short description for each project. **Briefly** review the rubric to get a sense of what students will do, but don't go too in-depth - we'll explore these projects later in this module.

### ⚾️ **Sequencing Project: Walk Up Songs**

#### <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1poW9kQYsXnBX2w7jCKhN9qjTbJ52qRDrn8jZf62S3-g/edit?tab=t.0" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Project Rubric</a>
#### Students create walk-up songs for characters from books or shows using triggers for dramatic effect and precise timing. This project introduces triggers as a tool for musical structure.

### 🐱 **Loops Project: Cat GIF Loops**

#### <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZW8gD3eA3lXAur9_PSC8nL2h6VJrcW2fBC3rxwm8Moc/edit?tab=t.0" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Project Rubric</a>
#### Students select a looping cat GIF and create a looping backing track that matches its mood. They explore how to use random blocks to make their music less predictable and more expressive.

### 🎶 **Functions Project: Genre Mash-Up**

#### <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FQAtWffIufswEhLG6LwZnyKSfnP7KG1nhthJi5w65bM/edit?tab=t.0" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Project Rubric</a>
#### Students remix an existing song into a new genre by using functions to define musical sections. They apply abstraction to organize code and explore how genre changes impact musical style and emotion.
